# **UNION in C Programming**
## What is a Union?
A **union** is a user-defined data type in C, similar to a **structure**, but with a key difference in memory usage:

**All members of a union share the same memory location.**

Hence, **only one member can hold a value at a time**.
## Defining a Union
### Syntax:
union tagname {

`    `datatype member1;

`    `datatype member2;

};
### Example:
union emp {

`    `int ID;

`    `char name[10];

`    `double salary;

} u;
## Accessing Union Members
Just like structures, union members are accessed using the **dot operator**.

Example:

u.ID = 101;

printf("%d", u.ID);
## Union vs Structure

|**Feature**|**Structure**|**Union**|
| :-: | :-: | :-: |
|Keyword used|struct|union|
|Memory Allocation|Separate memory for each member|Common memory shared by all members|
|Access|All members can be accessed at once|Only one member can be used at a time|
|Memory Used|Sum of memory of all members|Memory of the largest member only|
|Use Case|Use when all members are needed|Use when only one member at a time|
## Memory Allocation Example
### Structure:
struct emp {

`    `int ID;           // 2 bytes

`    `char name[10];    // 10 bytes

`    `double salary;    // 8 bytes

};

**Total memory used**: 2 + 10 + 8 = 20 bytes (actual depends on alignment, may be more)
### Union:
union emp {

`    `int ID;

`    `char name[10];

`    `double salary;

};

**Total memory used**: 8 bytes (largest member = double)

Structure vs Union Initialization

- **Structure**: All members can be initialized because they have separate memory.
- **Union**: Only one member can be initialized at a time. Initializing multiple members leads to data loss or error.
## Example Program: Union
